content:
[
{
  "Sentence 1": [
    "Text": "In 1955 V. C. WYNNE-EDWARDS published a paper on low reproductive rates in certain birds.",
    "Sentiment": 5,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "LACK",  "Reference sentiment": 2 }
    ],
    "Theory": [
      {"Theory name": "natural selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7},
      {"Theory name": "population genetics",  "Theory sentiment": 5},
      {"Theory name": "group selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7}
    ]
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 2": [
    "Text": "This paper contained important arguments against views expounded with, what appeared to be strict and irrefutable logic, by LACK (e.g.",
    "Sentiment": 4,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "LACK",  "Reference sentiment": 2}
    ],
    "Theory": [
      {"Theory name": "natural selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7},
      {"Theory name": "population genetics",  "Theory sentiment": 5},
      {"Theory name": "group selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7}
    ]
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 3": [
    "Text": "Lack maintains that if, e.g., some individuals in a bird population (on account of hereditary difference), lay more eggs than others, and thus, on an average, leave a greater number of descendants, the result will be an increase of fertility to the point where the parents are unable to procure enough food for the offspring.",
    "Sentiment": 2,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "LACK",  "Reference sentiment": 2}
    ],
    "Theory": [
      {"Theory name": "natural selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7},
      {"Theory name": "population genetics",  "Theory sentiment": 5},
      {"Theory name": "group selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7}
    ]
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 4": [
    "Text": "It may be argued and this is the line taken by W.-E.both in the paper mentioned and in the book under reviewthat Lack's view rests on a mistaken notion of natural selection.",
    "Sentiment": 4,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "W.-E.",  "Reference sentiment": 5 },
      { "Reference name": "LACK",  "Reference sentiment": 2 }
    ],
    "Theory": [
      {"Theory name": "natural selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7},
      {"Theory name": "population genetics",  "Theory sentiment": 5},
      {"Theory name": "group selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7}
    ]
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 5": [
    "Text": "The process of selection works, not only between individuals, but also between groups and between species, thus promoting characters which are to the benefit of the group, even in the face of contrary individual selection which may be kept in check by special devices.",
    "Sentiment": 7,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "W.-E.",  "Reference sentiment": 5 },
      { "Reference name": "WRIGHT",  "Reference sentiment": 5 }
    ],
    "Theory": [
      {"Theory name": "natural selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7},
      {"Theory name": "population genetics",  "Theory sentiment": 5},
      {"Theory name": "group selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7}
    ]
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 6": [
    "Text": "The existence of such evolutionary mechanisms is not only called for by a great many otherwise unaccountable facts, but is also in accordance with genetic evolutionary theory (see e.g.",
    "Sentiment": 6,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "WRIGHT",  "Reference sentiment": 5 }
    ],
    "Theory": [
      {"Theory name": "natural selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7},
      {"Theory name": "population genetics",  "Theory sentiment": 5},
      {"Theory name": "group selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7}
    ]
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 7": [
    "Text": "Since the bulk of what follows will be in a critical vein, it would be as well to begin by stating that on this main point I am in perfect accordance with Wynne-Edwards.",
    "Sentiment": 5,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "Wynne-Edwards",  "Reference sentiment": 7 }
    ],
    "Theory" : []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 8": [
    "Text": "In fact, about 10 years ago, I wrote some books for Scandinavian readers (1952, 1953, and 1954) in which the importance of intergroup selection in connection with many points concerning social adaptation were stressed.",
    "Sentiment": 7,
    "References": [],
    "Theory": [
      {"Theory name": "group selection",  "Theory sentiment": 7}
    ]
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 9": [
    "Text": "0. KALELA, who was concerned with the same problems, wrote, simultanously, notes which were still less accessible to most biologists owing to the fact they were written in Finnish.",
    "Sentiment": 5,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "KALELA",  "Reference sentiment": 5 }
    ],
    "Theory": []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 10": [
    "Text": "However, in 1954 he finally published a paper in German which, I think, is up to now one of the best introductions to the topic.",
    "Sentiment": 7,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "KALELA",  "Reference sentiment": 5 }
    ],
    "Theory": []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 11": [
    "Text": "It may be recommended in cases where critical readers of Wynne-Edwards' book, with little previous knowledge of vertebrate \"socio-ecology\", have been so scared by wild or even absurd theories that they are inclined to throw the baby out with the bath water.",
    "Sentiment": 3,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "Wynne-Edwards",  "Reference sentiment": 7 }
    ],
    "Theory": []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 12": [
    "Text": "Among biologists who have laid the foundation for the notion of auto-regulating mechanisms, it is easy for Scandinavians to remember our good friend P.",
    "Sentiment": 6,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "ERRING-TON",  "Reference sentiment": 7 }
    ],
    "Theory" : []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 13": [
    "Text": "L. ERRING-TON, who has again and again, especially in connection with his life-long work on the muskratstressed the decisive influence of the mutual tolerance or aggression of the animals themselves, in regulating numbers.",
    "Sentiment": 6,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "ERRING-TON",  "Reference sentiment": 7 }
    ],
    "Theory": []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 14": [
    "Text": "His work is only casually mentioned by W.-E.",
    "Sentiment": 4,
    "References": [
      { "Reference name": "W.-E.",  "Reference sentiment": 5 },
      { "Reference name": "ERRING-TON",  "Reference sentiment": 7 }
    ],
    "Theory": []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 15": [
    "Text": "On the whole, considering the enormous size of the book and the many rather peripheral topics treated, it is surprising how incompletely the really pertinent points are reviewed.",
    "Sentiment": 4,
    "References": [],
    "Theory": []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 16": [
    "Text": "I think it may be said of the book, with a certain amount of truth, that most of what is sound in it is not new, and most of which is new is not sound.",
    "Sentiment": 2,
    "References": [],
    "Theory": []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 17": [
    "Text": "This in itself might not have been a very serious objection.",
    "Sentiment": 5,
    "References": [],
    "Theory": []
  }
},
{
  "Sentence 18": [
    "Text": "If it had contained a good, well-digested, and balanced summary of facts and views on animals density regulation in relation to social behaviour, together with a clear statement of the problems (and on this foundation a statement of the more extreme theories of the author), it might have been a highly useful book.",
    "Sentiment": 7,
    "References": [],
    "Theory": []
  }
}
]

[
  {
    "Sentence 1": {
      "Text": "Institutions such as these, and also 'peck order' (the fact that individuals in a flock are generally of unequal status, thus ensuring that some may undergo times of hardship and maintain excellent health while others perish), conform to W.-E.'s contention that actual fighting over food is avoided by 'conventional competition'.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [
        {"Reference name": "W.-E.", "Reference sentiment": 7}
      ],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Conventional competition", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"}
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 2": {
      "Text": "It may be said that while food or a mate or other requisites inside the habitat constitute the ultimate goal, the proximate goal is territory or social status.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 3": {
      "Text": "Furthermore, fighting is usually highly ritualized.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 4": {
      "Text": "By this means actual bloodshed, which might be detrimental to the group and to the species in general, is minimized.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 5": {
      "Text": "Ritualization of this kind belongs to social traits of which the origin is incomprehensible without intergroup selection.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Inter-group selection", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"}
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 6": {
      "Text": "Teritoriality is also known in some fish and arthropods.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 7": {
      "Text": "Good evidence for true hierarchies in lower vertebrates and in invertebrates is meagre.",
      "Sentiment": 3,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 8": {
      "Text": "Nevertheless, the author is at considerable pains to push the beginning of competition for conventional goals very far back in the animal kingdom.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Conventional competition", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"}
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 9": {
      "Text": "It is his theory that \"it is precisely in this ... that social organisation and the primitive seeds of all social behaviour have their origin\", \". . .",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Social organization", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"},
        {"Theory name": "Primitive seeds of social behavior", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"}
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 10": {
      "Text": "a society can be defined for our purposes as an organisation capable of providing conventional competition: this, at least, appears to be its original, most primitive function, which indeed survives more or less thinly veiled even in the civilised societies of man.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Conventional competition", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"}
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 11": {
      "Text": "The author seems to have arrived at this highly improbable conclusion by a deplorable propensity to include very different phenomena under the same heading.",
      "Sentiment": 2,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Classification of phenomena", "Theory sentiment": "Against"}
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 12": {
      "Text": "At least, he often fails to take account of very deep seated dissimilarities.",
      "Sentiment": 2,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 13": {
      "Text": "For instance, the follow-my-leader reaction of the processionary caterpillars is mentioned as an example of (inborn) conventional behaviour (p. 449), and on p. 127 we find the following sentences: \"the barnacle larva which at metamorphosis fixes itself or is inhibited from doing so, depending on the presence and number of other barnacle larvae already attached, is responding socially in a way that is not effectively different in principle from the one which animates the communal behaviour of the social insects or the most highly socialised birds and mammals.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Conventional behavior in processionary caterpillars", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"},
        {"Theory name": "Social behavior in barnacle larva", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"} 
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 14": {
      "Text": "In each case the behaviour of the individual is conditioned by the presence and actions of other members of the population in the interests of regulating the dispersion of the group as a whole.'\"",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Regulation of population dispersion", "Theory sentiment": "Supportive"}
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 15": {
      "Text": "The fact that large tadpoles produce substances that powerfully inhibit or arrest the growth of small tadpoles (p. 558) is highly interesting as a 'homeostatic mechanism', but, as far as one can see, it has nothing to do with 'conventional competition'.",
      "Sentiment": 6,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Homeostatic mechanism", "Theory sentiment": "Descriptive"}
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Sentence 16": {
      "Text": "The same may be said of most of the well-attested cases of auto-regulation in animals other than birds and mammals.",
      "Sentiment": 4,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Auto-regulation in animals", "Theory sentiment": "Descriptive"}
      ]
    }
  }
]

{ "Sentence 1": [
      "Text": "The exact age when the fright-reaction first occurs in the young is determined in some species: Phoxinus laevis 51 days, Leuciscus leuciscus 59 days, and in Rhodeus amarus 40 days after the young left the mussel, where they developed.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Population genetics",  "Theory sentiment": "descriptive"}
      ]
  },
  { "Sentence 2" : [
      "Text": "Even if the 'alarm substance' is formed in the skin of the young some time before they themselves begin to show the reaction, there will still be time for them to be thinned out by the adults. ",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Group selection",  "Theory sentiment": "supportive"}
      ]
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 3" : [
      "Text": "(N.B. Here, again, is a social reaction the origin of which is only understandable by intergroup selection).",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        {"Theory name": "Group selection",  "Theory sentiment": "supportive"},
        {"Theory name": "Natural selection",  "Theory sentiment": "against"}
      ]
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 4" : [
      "Text": "Now, to revert to W.-E.'s ideas, it would certainly be carrying them very far in absurdum to maintain that social status is involved because the young are eaten by the mother and not the other way round, and, in any case, it is difficult to find any conventional competition in all this.",
      "Sentiment": 1,
      "References": ["W.-E."],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 5" : [
      "Text": "However, the author's favourite means for carrying such notions far back into the animal kingdom is the postulation of what he calls epideictic manifestations, instruments presumed to assess the population's own density and for becoming appropriately conditioned by it.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 6" : [
      "Text": "The result of this conditioning is supposed to be control of the subsequent breeding output or dispersionary measures by emigration and the like.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 7" : [
      "Text": "Gatherings of the most diverse kinds are believed to have this function: communal nuptial displays, 'leks', aggregations for social roosting or hibernationeven the vertical migration of planktonic animals!",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 8" : [
      "Text": "The latter are thought to concentrate near the surface at fixed times of the day for 'epideictic' reasons.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 9" : [
      "Text": "It is difficult, to say the least, to see how this conditioning could come about and in what way it could influence the reproductive output.",
      "Sentiment": 1,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 10" : [
      "Text": "The bogong moth, to take an example, (p. 314), forms immense aestivating aggregations in clefts and caves of granite outcrops on selected mountain tops in the Australian Alps of New South Wales.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": ["p. 314"],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 11" : [
      "Text": "What difference would it make for the single moth (even with so much milling around) whether there be one or two million moths present in a particular year, and how could this influence its subsequent reproductive output?",
      "Sentiment": 1,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 12" : [
      "Text": "As a reason for believing that assemblages of this kind must have some special significance, the author maintains that, even if the finding of especially favoured sites for hibernation or roosting may thus be ensured, the gatherings may be harmful in making the population in question more vulnerable to predatory attack.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 13" : [
      "Text": "Dr. ELLINOR BRO LARSEN has suggested to me an explanation involving exactly the opposite view.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": ["ELLINOR BRO LARSEN"],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 14" : [
      "Text": "In her experience, even if a particular insect species is acceptable to a particular predator, protracted feeding experiments often show that the predator cannot eat more than a few individuals, it refuses to take more, and it may even show evidence of ill-effects.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 15" : [
      "Text": "Thus, the prey-species in question appears to be mildly poisonous (e.g. various ladybirds and some collembola).",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },
  { "Sentence 16" : [
      "Text": "In such cases the population may be better protected by being massed together, even if the animals are easier to find than in cases of individual hibernation or roosting.",
      "Sentiment": 9,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  }
]

{ "Sentence 1": [
      "Text":  "Just one more example of animal aggregations must be mentioned owing to a curious statement in the description of the swarming of whirligig beetles (Gyrinidae).",
      "Sentiment": 4,
      "References": [
          {"Reference name": "WESENBERG-LUND",  "Reference sentiment": 7}
      ],
      "Theory": []
  },

  { "Sentence 2": [
      "Text": "Perhaps there is confusion here with the behaviour of the larvae?",
      "Sentiment": 3,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 3": [
      "Text": "We now come, finally, to that part of the book which, in my opinion, deserves the most violent opposition.",
      "Sentiment": 1,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 4": [
      "Text": "I am alluding, of course, to the idea of an 'understanding' between competitors for the same resources.",
      "Sentiment": 2,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
          {"Theory name": "Gause's hypothesis", "Theory sentiment": "against"}
      ]
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 5": [
      "Text": "By interspecific conventions an auto-regulatory mechanism for two or several species together should be built up, similar to that existing within single species.",
      "Sentiment": 4,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 6": [
      "Text": "This is sometimes believed to be so to the extent of presenting \"a radical antithesis to Gause's hypothesis that animals of similar ecology cannot survive together in the same habitat\" (p. 18).",
      "Sentiment": 3,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
          {"Theory name": "Gause's hypothesis", "Theory sentiment": "against"}
      ]
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 7": [
      "Text": "The wording in chapters 17 and 18, where these ideas are expounded, is extremely woolly and it is difficult to give a strictly correct presentation of them.",
      "Sentiment": 2,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 8": [
      "Text": "It is said that a complete partition of resources between different species is likely to involve narrower specialisation, with the final result that each species is confined to relatively few kinds of food-organisms, with a corresponding loss of resilience and stability should any of these fail (p. 395).",
      "Sentiment": 4,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 9": [
      "Text": "Therefore, it may be an advantage \"to enter into various kinds of social and epideictic union, apparently for the purpose of syndicating their dispersion and mutually conserving common resources\" (p. 419).",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 10": [
      "Text": "\"The adaptive value of mixed colonies comes primarily from the need, among species with overlapping food resources, to take cognisance of the numbers of their competitors in regulating their own populations\" (p. 420).",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 11": [
      "Text": "The cautious wording here, and various other signs of the author's uneasiness in these chapters, show that he is not quite unaware of the difficulties (to say the least) of this view.",
      "Sentiment": 3,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 12": [
      "Text": "By what kind of evolutionary mechanism could such a mutual regulation come about?",
      "Sentiment": 2,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 13": [
      "Text": "But it appears that the expression \"take cognisance of\" must mean that the breeding output is to some extent regulated according to the total number of individuals belonging to different species.",
      "Sentiment": 4,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 14": [
      "Text": "Of various closely related species which are difficult to tell apart by visual means (e.g. the species of Vespula) the author thinks that the resemblance may have been evolved, partly at least, for the sake of mutual integration.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 15": [
      "Text": "Among the examples mentioned we find, somewhat surprisingly, bees of the genus Halictus, of which there are many very similar species (some of them show beginnings of sociality, but this seems immaterial in the present connection).",
      "Sentiment": 4,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 16": [
      "Text": "Sometimes very similar species nest together.",
      "Sentiment": 4,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  },

  { "Sentence 17": [
      "Text": "It is apparently forgotten that in these bees an egg is never laid until food has been gathered for the larva in question, and furthermore the resources, honey and pollen, are not easily depleted, so here additional regulating mechanisms seem quite unnecessary.",
      "Sentiment": 3,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
   ]
  }
]

{ "Sentence 1": [
      "Text":  "The term dispersion has been borrowed from LACK (1954, p. 264) where it means the non-random type of distribution of a species (of birds in particular) within suitable habitats.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [
        { "Reference name": "LACK",  "Reference sentiment": 5}
      ],
      "Theory": []
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 2" : [
      "Text": "As a rule, it is easy to see that individuals are dispersed in an appropriate way with respect to food-supply, and Lack himself was in some doubt as to how this was brought about.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [
        { "Reference name": "LACK",  "Reference sentiment": 5}
      ],
      "Theory": []
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 3" : [
      "Text": "Obviously there is some involvement here of the habitat selection mechanism, i.e. the mechanism that leads populations into the habitat where, in the long run, they are able to compete.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        { "Theory name": "habitat selection mechanism",  "Theory sentiment": "supportive"}
      ]
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 4" : [
      "Text": "It may even be impossible to make a clear-cut division between these concepts, but the emphasis is somewhat different.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 5" : [
      "Text": "This is not discussed in the book.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 6" : [
      "Text": "W.-E. merely writes (p. 1) that dispersion may be defined to include habitat selection.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        { "Theory name": "habitat selection",  "Theory sentiment": "supportive"}
      ]
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 7" : [
      "Text": "There is no review of present knowledge of habitat selection, e.g. in birds.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        { "Theory name": "habitat selection",  "Theory sentiment": "supportive"}
      ]
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 8" : [
      "Text": "This is rather unimportant, however, in comparison with the failure in some sections of the book, to distinguish between dispersion and regulation of (total) numbers.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": [
        { "Theory name": "dispersion",  "Theory sentiment": "against"},
        { "Theory name": "regulation of numbers",  "Theory sentiment": "supportive"}
      ]
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 9" : [
      "Text": "On many occasions one has to simply guess which is meant, and the reader may be carried imperceptibly from one concept to the other.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 10" : [
      "Text": "However, after this necessary digression, we may revert to the question of competition between different species for the same food.",
      "Sentiment": 5,
      "References": [],
      "Theory": []
    ]
  },
  { "Sentence 11" : [
